The ox drinks first when the master is patient, but the hasty man spills his own water.
The field yields more to the hand that waits for rain than to the tongue that curses the sky.
The heart grows tired before the plow does; rest it or it will break your harvest.
The goat knows which child will feed it, and which only throws stones for laughter.
The bread shared at dawn tastes sweeter than the feast taken alone in pride.
The neighbor who hears your cry at night is worth ten friends in the marketplace.
The fig ripens unseen until the sun remembers it; so too with a quiet mans fortune.
The well runs dry faster for those who boast of its depth.
The hand that hides its grain invites hunger before winters end.
The road teaches more than the teacher who has never walked it.
I will rise before the sun, for the lazy mans field feeds only crows.
I know the measure of a man by how he gives bread, not how he eats it.
I remember when the rains failed, and the proud bowed lower than the donkeys.
I speak softly to strangers, for angels once came to Abraham in the dust.
I trust the man who mends his sandals, not the one who counts anothers faults.
I have seen envy burn a hut faster than firewood.
I say truth travels slower than rumor, but it never loses its way.
I would rather lose a coin in kindness than find one in deceit.
I walk behind my ox, not before it; the furrow must follow, not lead.
I fear only the silence of God, not the noise of men.
You will reap what your tongue sows before your hands ever touch the earth.
You cannot hide a lie from your own sleep; it wakes you before the rooster.
You walk as your father taught, even if your feet deny it.
You think the rich mans door is open, but his heart is not.
You give salt to a neighbor, he will lend you his fire when winter comes.
You carry your anger like a jar with cracks; it spills before reaching home.
You should mend the roof when the stars are kind, not when the storm shouts.
You may boast of your sheep, but count them after the wolf leaves.
You cannot plant peace where envy plows.
You will find no rest chasing another mans shadow.
Do not speak of rain while another mans roof leaks.
Do your work as if no eye sees; the Lord does.
Do not call the poor lazy until you have carried their burden for a mile.
Do not trade truth for silver; both lose their shine.
Do not mock the fool, for he teaches wisdom without knowing.
Do not boast of tomorrows harvest; the locust has not spoken yet.
Do not judge a womans heart by her jars weight.
Do what is right even when the market laughs.
Do not chase a dog with a bone in its mouth—youll get neither bone nor peace.
Do remember the drought when your cup overflows.
That which is given in secret is counted louder in heaven.
That man is rich who owes nothing but kindness.
That word you swallow today may save your teeth tomorrow.
That path of stones leads to peace if walked with humility.
That stranger at your gate might carry your blessing or your test.
That cup of cold water may cool more than thirst.
That seed buried in doubt will never see the sun.
That day will come when the liar forgets his lie but not its cost.
That hand you slap may one day feed your son.
That silence after anger is the beginning of wisdom.
And when the sun burns hottest, remember the shadow it casts is your rest.
And if your brother falls, lift him before asking why he stumbled.
And though the road is long, the dust remembers your patience.
And when all words fail, let your work speak.
And if you lend, lend without counting, or it is not mercy.
And when your field is full, leave a corner for the hungry.
And if you forget kindness, the earth will forget your footsteps.
And when you speak, weigh your words as you weigh your grain.
And though night covers you, light your lamp for another.
And when your heart is proud, listen to the wind—it carries no crown.
The stone remembers every foot that stepped on it, though none remember the stone.
The child who listens learns faster than the man who argues.
The sparrow eats what it finds, not what it dreams.
The old jar holds the sweetest wine.
The ear that hears correction is richer than the hand that holds gold.
The market is loud, but truth whispers by the well.
The vine climbs the wall that gives it shade, not the one that boasts of height.
The donkey walks straight though its master wanders.
The storm passes; the stubborn tree breaks.
The neighbors smoke tells you more than his words.
The night hides no secret from a praying heart.
The hand that gives before asked never grows empty.
The eyes of the hungry see more than the full mans wisdom.
The shepherd counts by love, not by number.
The mouth that curses rain shall thirst longest.
The fig tree blooms for the patient alone.
The wind that bends the grass spares the tree that bows.
I saw men fight over dust and lose their peace for nothing.
I trade my rest for bread, but not my honor for coin.
I keep silent when the wise speak, for echoing wisdom is better than inventing folly.
I would rather break my back than my word.
I tell my sons: a slow step lasts longer than a loud boast.
I have known joy only after losing what I thought I needed.
I hear the voice of truth most clearly when my stomach is empty.
I plant though the locust flew last year.
I lend a hand to those who cursed me, and my sleep is still sweet.
I learned that mercy grows faster than barley in wet soil.
I watch the moon and remember that light can borrow.
I take comfort in work; the idle man feeds his fears.
I forgive because the field forgets every footprint by spring.
I walk with my head low so the Lord may see my heart.
I have found that silence is the only honest answer to pride.
I return good for evil not because they deserve it, but because I do.
I keep my tongue as I keep my ox—well bridled and seldom driven.
You judge a man not by his robe but by his shadow in the sun.
You build walls with words when silence would have kept peace.
You think the drought is cruel; the proud think the same of patience.
You will find no blessing in bread gained by deceit.
You cant draw water from a well you mock.
You are strong until hunger asks your heart a question.
You speak too fast and lose the wisdom you meant to share.
You find the way home by helping another find his.
You give thanks, and the Lord multiplies your peace.
You may forget your promise, but heaven does not.
You cannot walk two roads and reach one village.
You will know a friend when your field is barren.
You hear truth in the mouth of children if your pride sleeps.
You mend fences faster with bread than with anger.
You dream of wealth while your jar leaks oil.
You should fear the man who smiles while plotting silence.
You cannot chase peace and envy in the same hour.
Do not plow anger into the field of morning.
Do remember that the sun rises for both thief and shepherd.
Do not measure kindness by its witness.
Do what must be done before the rooster counts the hours.
Do not drink wine and speak judgment.
Do not promise faster than you can walk.
Do not curse the stone that broke your jar; it held the path still.
Do mend your words before they leave your lips.
Do not fear the small beginnings, for mustard grows mighty.
Do not repay insult with insult; repay it with indifference.
Do carry peace as you carry bread—daily and humbly.
Do not mock the slow worker; he finishes what the quick forgets.
Do not call a day evil until the sun sets.
Do not turn your face from tears; tomorrow they may be yours.
Do remember the hand that taught you to sow.
Do not despise old tools; they built your roof.
Do speak truth even if it empties your purse.
That which grows in shadow still owes life to the sun.
That fool who listens once is wiser than the proud who never bend.
That coin you hide will rust before it blesses anyone.
That silence after anger is worth a measure of silver.
That lamb that wanders may teach the shepherd to watch his heart.
That woman who speaks softly rules her home without shouting.
That road you fear may lead to your answer.
That dream that repeats may be a warning, not a promise.
That man who forgets mercy soon finds himself alone at harvest.
That word unspoken saves ten that must later be begged back.
That well dug in faith will fill though the sky is still blue.
That storm you curse waters your next planting.
That cup you refused in pride might have been your healing.
That shadow lengthens to remind you the day is never yours.
That hope kept alive in drought is worship enough.
That fruit untasted by the planter is sweetest to his children.
That wound covered too soon will fester in peace.
And when your ox stumbles, thank God you still have ground.
And if you must lie, lie only to spare anothers shame.
And when rain falls on your enemys roof, bless it still.
And if the wind steals your roof, let faith rebuild before your hands.
And when your lamp burns low, remember who first gave you oil.
And if hunger knocks, share what remains.
And when the dogs bark, check first that they bark not at your pride.
And though men forget, heaven keeps the ledger.
And if a stranger greets you, answer as if God listens.
And when night grows cold, be the fire for another.
And if your field fails, your hands still hold prayer.
And though friends fade, mercy never withers.
And if anger visits, do not let it stay the night.
And when your heart is full, empty your jar for the thirsty.
And if laughter leaves your house, sing until it returns.
And when the child cries, the village is tested.
And if your tongue burns, your truth was too sharp.
The shepherds whistle carries farther than the rich mans boast.
The clay pot that cracks in the fire teaches the potter patience.
The morning wind forgives the dust of yesterday.
The child who forgets his fathers voice forgets his own name.
The field remembers who labored and who merely watched.
The sparrow does not count the seeds it eats; it trusts the earth to give more.
The fool drinks deep before the water clears.
The donkey returns to the well that never mocked his thirst.
The hands that share the yoke learn the same ache and the same rest.
The bread of peace is baked in the oven of restraint.
I keep my heart small so it may fit in heavens hand.
I cannot buy wisdom, but I can pay attention.
I will not trade my peace for another mans praise.
I learned more from a broken tool than from a full purse.
I fear the smooth road; it hides no lessons.
I take counsel from old scars more than young mouths.
I will eat little but speak less.
I forgive quickly so my sleep stays quiet.
I guard my tongue as I guard my fire—never let it wander.
I remember when a good neighbor was richer than gold.
You owe the truth even to those who will not thank you.
You will not taste joy if bitterness sits first at your table.
You cannot water two fields with one bucket.
You should keep your promise though no one remembers it.
You will see pride fall faster than a fig in wind.
You may trust a poor mans blessing more than a princes smile.
You will find comfort where you stopped to listen.
You cannot eat words once spoken.
You may lose a coin, not a conscience.
You will carry peace as long as you feed mercy.
Do not pour new wine into a cracked jug.
Do remember the beggars eyes when you eat in plenty.
Do not chase the wind; it always wins.
Do walk slow enough to notice gratitude.
Do not despise the day that teaches patience.
Do gather wisdom as ants gather grain—small and steady.
Do not hide kindness; it shines brighter in famine.
Do trust the one who prays before speaking.
Do not step over a hungry man to reach a feast.
Do mend your heart as carefully as your roof.
