That man who listens to rebuke saves his field from ruin.
That morning when the rain fell, the land forgave our pride.
That coin given in secret weighs nothing on the soul.
That song sung in sorrow becomes a prayer by nightfall.
That woman who shares her last flour teaches faith better than priests.
That gate you close in anger will bar your joy tomorrow.
That silence between brothers is heavier than stone.
That river you cross in haste may never let you return.
That tear unseen by men is counted by heaven.
And when you reap, leave some grain for the forgotten.
And if your ox grows weary, rest it before it breaks.
And though the sky darkens, remember the stars still wait.
And when your heart hardens, water it with compassion.
And if the road splits, take the one that humbles you.
And when the well is deep, lower your pride first.
And if your lamp burns low, lend it air, not complaint.
And when friends quarrel, be the quiet between them.
And though age bends your back, let it not bend your mercy.
And when you die, leave no debt but love.
The man who boasts of strength has not yet carried grief.
The olive tree bends and lives; the cedar breaks and is proud.
The lamp that burns through the night teaches patience to the watcher.
The dog that guards for bread will bark for anyone with a crust.
I walk slower now, but my peace walks with me.
I give thanks for small mercies; they teach larger ones to come.
I have no gold, but I have time for those who knock.
I wait for answers only after I have tilled my field.
You will forget insults faster than hunger, so feed the poor before arguing.
You cannot bless and curse from the same mouth.
You will find truth where no one is shouting.
You should listen to the quiet man at the gate; he has seen more than priests.
Do not count your cattle while the wolves still howl.
Do speak softly when truth is heavy.
Do not chase anothers path and expect your own blessing.
Do what good you can before sunset, for dawn is not promised.
That dust on your sandals is holier than the palace floor.
That promise whispered is louder in heaven than a vow shouted.
That poor mans prayer is a seed that never dies.
That word of comfort can mend more than a coin can buy.
And when you are wronged, plant mercy, not memory.
And if laughter visits, open the door wide.
And when your hands are empty, lift them higher.
